  "prompt": "What is the difference between enum, union and struct in C programming?",
  "response": "In C programming, `enum`, `union`, and `struct` are all user-defined data types, but they serve different purposes and have different behaviors. Let\u2019s break down each one:\n\n### Enum\n- **Definition**: `enum` (short for enumeration) is a data type that consists of a set of named integer constants. It is used to define variables that can hold a set of predefined values.\n- **Usage**: The values of an enum type are symbolic names (like constants) which can make the code more readable.\n- **Declaration**:\n  ```c\n  enum Day { SUNDAY, MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY, THURSDAY, FRIDAY, SATURDAY };\n  ```\n- **Behavior**: Each name in an enum is associated with an integer value starting from 0 by default. You can specify the starting value or assign specific values to some of the names. For instance:\n  ```c\n  enum Color { RED = 1, GREEN = 2, BLUE = 4 };\n  ```\n\n### Struct\n- **Definition**: `struct` (short for structure) is a composite data type that groups multiple variables (of potentially different types) under a single name. Each variable inside a struct is called a member or field.\n- **Usage**: Structs are used to create complex data types that model a real-world entity by holding related data together.\n- **Declaration**:\n  ```c\n  struct Person {\n      char name[50];\n      int age;\n      float height;\n  };\n  ```\n- **Behavior**: Each member of a struct has its own storage, and you can access each member using the dot `.` operator if you have an instance of the struct.\n\n### Union\n- **Definition**: `union` is similar to a struct in that it groups multiple variables under a single name, but all members of a union share the same memory location. This means a union can hold only one of its members at a time, and the size of a union is determined by the size of its largest member.\n- **Usage**: Unions are used sometimes for memory optimization when you need to save space and you know that only one of the members will be used at a time.\n- **Declaration**:\n  ```c\n  union Data {\n      int integer;\n      float floatingPoint;\n      char character;\n  };\n  ```\n- **Behavior**: Accessing a member of a union will give you the value of the member that was most recently written to, and all members share the same memory space, so you have to be careful with which member you are using at any time.\n\n### Summary\n- **Enum**: A type that represents named integer constants. Used for creating a set of related constants.\n- **Struct**: A composite data type that groups variables of different types. Used for modeling a composite entity.\n- **Union**: A composite data type similar to a struct but uses shared memory for its members. Only one member can be active at a time. \n\nThese constructs help in designing complex data types in C and are fundamental to effective data organization and representation in the language.",
